[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The Android software development kit (SDK) includes a comprehensive set of development tools.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The Android SDK Platform Tools are a separately downloadable subset of the full SDK, consisting of command-line tools such as `adb` and `fastboot`.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The Android Debug Bridge (ADB) is a tool to run commands on a connected Android device.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Fastboot is a protocol used for flashing filesystems.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Code written in C/C++ can be compiled to ARM, or x86 native code (or their 64-bit variants) using the Android Native Development Kit (NDK).
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The Android 3.1 platform (also backported to Android 2.3.4) introduces Android Open Accessory support, which allows external USB hardware (an Android USB accessory) to interact with an Android-powered device in a special "accessory" mode.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] When an Android-powered device is in accessory mode, the connected accessory acts as the USB host (powers the bus and enumerates devices) and the Android-powered device acts as the USB device.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Android USB accessories are specifically designed to attach to Android-powered devices and adhere to a simple protocol (Android accessory protocol) that allows them to detect Android-powered devices that support accessory mode.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Development tools intended to help an Android device interact with external electronics include IOIO, Android Open Accessory Development Kit, Microbridge, Triggertrap, etc.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The Android Developer Challenge was a competition to find the most innovative application for Android.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Google offered prizes totaling 10 million US dollars, distributed between ADC I and ADC II.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] ADC I accepted submissions from January 2 to April 14, 2008.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The 50 most promising entries, announced on May 12, 2008, each received a $25,000 award to further development.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] It ended in early September with the announcement of ten teams that received $275,000 each, and ten teams that received $100,000 each.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The first round of the ADC II closed on October 6, 2009.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The first-round winners of ADC II comprising the top 200 applications were announced on November 5, 2009.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Voting for the second round also opened on the same day and ended on November 25.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Google announced the top winners of ADC II on November 30, with SweetDreams, What the Doodle!? and WaveSecure being nominated the overall winners of the challenge.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] There is a community of open source enthusiasts that build and share Android-based distributions (i.e. firmware) with a number of customizations and additional features, such as FLAC lossless audio support and the ability to store downloaded applications on the microSD card.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] This usually involves rooting the device.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Rooting allows users root access to the operating system, enabling full control of the phone.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Rooting has several disadvantages as well, including increased risk of hacking, high chances of bricking, losing warranty, increased virus attack risks, etc.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] It is also possible to install custom firmware, although the device's boot loader must also be unlocked.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Custom firmware allows users of older phones to use applications available only on newer releases.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Those firmware packages are updated frequently, incorporate elements of Android functionality that haven't yet been officially released within a carrier-sanctioned firmware, and tend to have fewer limitations.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] CyanogenMod and OMFGB are examples of such firmware.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] On September 24, 2009, Google issued a cease and desist letter to the modder Cyanogen, citing issues with the re-distribution of Google's closed-source applications within the custom firmware.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Even though most of Android OS is open source, phones come packaged with closed-source Google applications for functionality such as the Google Play and GPS navigation.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Google has asserted that these applications can only be provided through approved distribution channels by licensed distributors.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Cyanogen complied with Google's license and continued to distribute its mod without the proprietary software.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] It provided a method to backup licensed Google applications during the mod's install process and restore them when the process is complete.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Obstacles to development include the fact that Android does not use established Java standards, that is, Java SE and ME.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] This prevents compatibility between Java applications written for those platforms and those written for the Android platform.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Android reuses the Java language syntax and semantics, but it does not provide the full class libraries and APIs bundled with Java SE or ME.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] However, there are multiple tools in the market from companies such as Myriad Group and UpOnTek that provide Java ME to Android conversion services.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Android provides its own GUI classes, and does not provide Java AWT, Swing or JavaFX.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] It does not support the full Java Beans API.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Android was created by the Open Handset Alliance, which is led by Google.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The early feedback on developing applications for the Android platform was mixed.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Issues cited include bugs, lack of documentation, inadequate QA infrastructure, and no public issue-tracking system.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] (Google announced an issue tracker on January 18, 2008.) In December 2007, MergeLab mobile startup founder Adam MacBeth stated, "Functionality is not there, is poorly documented or just doesn't work...
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] It's clearly not ready for prime time." Despite this, Android-targeted applications began to appear the week after the platform was announced.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The first publicly available application was the Snake game.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] A preview release of the Android SDK was released on November 12, 2007.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] On July 15, 2008, the Android Developer Challenge Team accidentally sent an email to all entrants in the Android Developer Challenge announcing that a new release of the SDK was available in a "private" download area.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The email was intended for winners of the first round of the Android Developer Challenge.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] The revelation that Google was supplying new SDK releases to some developers and not others (and keeping this arrangement private) led to widely reported frustration within the Android developer community at the time.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] On August 18, 2008, the Android 0.9 SDK beta was released.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] This release provided an updated and extended API, improved development tools and an updated design for the home screen.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Detailed instructions for upgrading are available to those already working with an earlier release.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] On September 23, 2008, the Android 1.0 SDK (Release 1) was released.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] According to the release notes, it included "mainly bug fixes, although some smaller features were added." It also included several API changes from the 0.9 version.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Multiple versions have been released since it was developed.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] On December 5, 2008, Google announced the first Android Dev Phone, a SIM-unlocked and hardware-unlocked device that is designed for advanced developers.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] It was a modified version of HTC's Dream phone.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] While developers can use regular consumer devices to test and use their applications, some developers may choose a dedicated unlocked or no-contract device.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] As of July 2013, more than one million applications have been developed for Android, with over 25 billion downloads.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] A June 2011 research indicated that over 67% of mobile developers used the platform, at the time of publication.
[src:jetpack-compose/android-software-development] Android smartphone shipments ware forecast to exceed 1.2 billion units in 2018 with an 85% market share.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:jetpack-compose/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:jetpack-compose/graphical-widget] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] In Compose, a user interface is defined using functions that have been annotated with the `@Composable` annotation, which are known as composable functions and define the screen's state.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Jetpack Compose uses a Kotlin compiler plugin to transform composable functions into UI elements.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] The first preview of Jetpack Compose was announced at the Google I/O conference in May 2019.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] The developer preview was released in October 2019, and the alpha release occurred in August 2020.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Compose entered its beta phase in February 2021, with its first production release taking place that July.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Jetpack Compose supports Android 5.0 and later.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] It uses the Kotlin programming language, and provides a reactive programming model similar to other UI frameworks such as Flutter, Vue.js, and React Native.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Compose is designed to integrate seamlessly with existing Android apps and libraries, allowing developers to gradually migrate their apps to Compose.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] The annotation is used by the Compose compiler to generate the UI boilerplate code.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] When the state is updated, composable functions are called again with new data, which causes the widgets they emit to be redrawn in a process known as recomposition.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Recomposition is only performed for composable functions that need to be updated, which improves UI efficiency.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] The 1.0 release introduced Compose Preview, which is built into Android Studio starting with Arctic Fox.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] It allows composables to be previewed using different configurations without deploying the app to a device.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Jetpack Glance is a Jetpack Compose-based framework for developing widgets for Android.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Glance's first stable release occurred in September 2023.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] In September 2024, the 1.0 stable version of the Jetpack Compose application programming interfaces (APIs) for building adaptive UIs with Material 3 was released.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] When Jetpack Compose 1.0 was released, Google said, "There are already over 2,000 apps in the Play Store using Compose – in fact, the Play Store app itself uses Compose." As of October 2022, 16% of the top 1000 apps on the Play Store included Compose.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] The apps included those from companies such as Airbnb, Lyft, and Square.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] In May 2024, this number had grown to 40%.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] In 2022, Google detailed how it utilized Jetpack Compose as part of its rewrite of the Play Store app, stating that "writing UI requires much less code, sometimes up to 50%" and that the developers were able to improve the app's performance.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Google rewrote parts of Android's Settings app using Jetpack Compose in Android 14.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] Meta Platforms developed its Threads social media app in five months using Jetpack Compose.
[src:jetpack-compose/jetpack-compose] The Instagram for Android app has also been written using Jetpack Compose.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced Kotlin had become its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Since the release of Android Studio 3.0 in October 2017, Kotlin has been included as an alternative to the standard Java compiler.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin has support for the web with Kotlin/JS, through an intermediate representation-based backend that has been declared stable since version 1.8, released in December 2022.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin/Native (e.g., Apple silicon support) has been declared stable since version 1.9.20, released in November 2023.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] The name is derived from Kotlin Island, a Russian island in the Gulf of Finland, near Saint Petersburg.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Andrey Breslav, Kotlin's former lead designer, mentioned that the team decided to name it after an island, in imitation of the Java programming language, which shares a name with the Indonesian island of Java.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] The first commit to the Kotlin Git repository was on 8 November 2010.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] In July 2011, JetBrains unveiled Project Kotlin, a new JVM language that had been under development for a year.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains lead Dmitry Jemerov said that most languages lacked the features they were looking for, except for Scala.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] However, he cited Scala's slow compilation time as a deficiency.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] One of Kotlin's stated goals is to compile as quickly as Java.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] In February 2012, JetBrains open-sourced the project under the Apache 2 license.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] JetBrains expected Kotlin to drive sales of IntelliJ IDEA.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.0 was released on 15 February 2016, which is considered the first officially stable release, and JetBrains has committed to long-term backwards compatibility starting with this version.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] At Google I/O 2017, Google announced first-class support for Kotlin on Android.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] On 7 May 2019, Google announced that Kotlin is now its preferred language for Android app developers.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Development lead Andrey Breslav has said that Kotlin is designed to be an industrial-strength object-oriented language, a "better language" than Java, and still fully interoperable with Java code, allowing companies to make a gradual migration from Java to Kotlin.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Semicolons are optional as a statement terminator; in most cases, a newline is sufficient for the compiler to deduce that the statement has ended.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin variable declarations and parameter lists place the data type after the variable name (separated by a colon), similar to Ada, BASIC, Pascal, TypeScript, and Rust.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin 1.3 added support for contracts, which are stable for the standard library declarations, but still experimental for user-defined declarations.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Contracts are inspired by the design-by-contract programming paradigm.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Like Scala.js, Kotlin code can be transpiled to JavaScript, enabling interoperability between Kotlin and JavaScript and allowing either writing complete web applications in Kotlin or sharing code between a Kotlin backend and a JavaScript frontend.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Kotlin relaxes the Java restriction on static methods and variables, allowing them to exist outside a class body.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Static objects and functions can be defined at the top level of the package without requiring a redundant class-level scope.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] For compatibility with Java, Kotlin provides the `JvmName` annotation, which specifies the class name used when the package is viewed from a Java project.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] For example, `@file:JvmName("JavaClassName")`.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] As in C, C++, C#, Java, and Go, the entry point to a Kotlin program is a function named `main`, which may be passed an array containing any command-line arguments.
[src:jetpack-compose/kotlin-programming-language] Perl, PHP, and Unix shell–style string interpolation is supported.
